## Adding a New Benchmark: Smart Workflow

Adding a new benchmark should follow this checklist:

```text
1. Create folder: src/engine/benchmarks/packs/<benchmark-id>/
2. Add pack.json
3. Add scenario list
4. Add ranks if the benchmark has ranks
5. Add thresholds if available
6. Add aliases
7. Map native categories to universal categories
8. Add source metadata
9. Run pack validation
10. Add sample test runs
11. Add one engine test proving analysis works
12. Add UI option to select the pack
```

If the benchmark has no thresholds yet:
- add scenarios anyway
- set `hasThresholdData: false`
- engine uses progress-only mode

---

## Validation Is Mandatory

Every benchmark pack must pass validation before the app uses it.

Validation should check:

- pack has ID/name/version
- scenario IDs are unique
- rank IDs are unique
- thresholds reference existing scenarios
- thresholds reference existing ranks
- every scenario has universal category mapping
- every scenario has platform
- scoring direction is valid
- no duplicate aliases within the same pack
- threshold scores are numbers
- rank order is consistent

Invalid packs should not crash the app.

They should return a clear error:

```text
Benchmark pack "viscose" is invalid: threshold references missing scenario "xyz".
```

---

## Keep UI Simple

The UI should not know benchmark internals.

Bad UI logic:

```text
if benchmark == voltaic then show Voltaic rank
if benchmark == viscose then show Viscose rank
```

Good UI logic:

```text
analysis = engine.analyze({ runs, benchmarkId })
show analysis.currentRank
show analysis.progressToNextRank
show analysis.note
```

The engine and pack system handle details.

---

## Analysis Modes

Aim Brain should support:

### Benchmark Mode

One benchmark at a time.

Examples:
- Voltaic Mode
- Viscose Mode
- Custom Benchmark Mode

Shows native:
- ranks
- categories
- scenarios
- weaknesses
- benchmark progress

### Universal Aim Mode

Combines all supported data using universal categories.

Shows:
- static clicking
- dynamic clicking
- smooth tracking
- reactive tracking
- switching
- hybrid/other

This lets the app say:

```text
Reactive Tracking is weak across both Voltaic and Viscose.
```

### Comparison Mode

Compares benchmarks without lying.

Shows:
- native rank in each benchmark
- normalized progress
- shared weaknesses
- different category strengths

Never say:

```text
Voltaic Diamond = Viscose Rank X
```

Say:

```text
Voltaic Diamond maps to 62/100 normalized progress.
Viscose Rank X maps to 58/100 normalized progress.
```

---

## MVP Benchmark Pack Scope

Do not try to add every benchmark immediately.

MVP should include:

```text
1. Shared BenchmarkPack interface
2. Pack validator
3. Pack registry
4. Sample Voltaic pack
5. Sample Viscose pack
6. Progress-only fallback
7. Tests proving both packs work
```

Real full threshold data can be expanded later.

---

## Codex Instruction

When implementing, Codex should not hardcode Voltaic into engine functions.

Good function names:

```ts
analyzeBenchmarkProgress(runs, benchmarkPack)
matchScenario(run, benchmarkPack)
calculateRankProgress(score, scenario, benchmarkPack)
getProgressOnlyStats(runs)
```

Bad function names:

```ts
analyzeVoltaicProgress()
getVoltaicRank()
calculateVoltaicMasterReadiness()
```

Voltaic-specific names are only allowed inside:

```text
src/engine/benchmarks/packs/voltaic/
```

---

## Success Criteria

This benchmark pack system is successful when:

- a new benchmark can be added mostly by adding data
- the core engine does not change for every benchmark
- the UI does not contain benchmark-specific logic
- missing thresholds do not break analysis
- Voltaic and Viscose can both be analyzed by the same engine
- custom benchmarks can later be added without a rewrite
